<p><big> </big><big><br>
</big></p>
<p><big> </big></p>
<p><big>Since it is quite difficult to draw something that is  infinitely tall, we represent the Dirac with an arrow centered at the  point it is applied. The dirac delta function and unit impulse are shown in Figure 9(a) and 9(b) respectively.<br>
</big></p>
<p><big> </big></p>
<p><big>The impulse function has some special properties.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big> </big></p>
<ul><big>
    <ul type="disc">
        <li>&nbsp;The sampling property.</li>
    </ul>
    </big></ul>
    <p><big> </big></p>
    <p><big>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=df6b4ac4cf7d7e8e936115e9723d7cae.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mn»0«/mn»«mo»)«/mo»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></big></p>
    <p><big>     </big></p>
    <ul><big>
        <ul type="disc">
            <p><span style="display: none;" id="1317213280690S">&nbsp;</span></p>
            <li><big><span id="1318397709986S" style="display: none;">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</big>Another important property is the scaling property.</li>
            <p><span style="display: none;" id="1317213280843E">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </ul>
        </big></ul>
        <p><big>     </big></p>
        <p><big><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=55ecf8d449bbfd80a7e1c0c257c3c33c.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»§#945;«/mi»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mn»1«/mn»«mfenced close=¨|¨ open=¨|¨»«mi»§#945;«/mi»«/mfenced»«/mfrac»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></big></big></p>
        <p><big>         </big></p>
        <p><big>Since the derivative of the unit step<em> u(t)</em><em> </em>is zero everywhere except at<em> t=0</em>, the unit impulse is zero everywhere except at<em> t=0. </em>Since  the unit step is the integral of the unit impulse, a definite  integral of the unit impulse whose integration range includes<em> t=0</em> must  have the value one.</big></p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=67a63315489c6a57b8caa1ecf9d84a78.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mi»d«/mi»«mrow»«mi»d«/mi»«mi»t«/mi»«/mrow»«/mfrac»«mi»u«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle">, where <em>u(t)</em> is the unit step.</big></p>
        <p>&nbsp;<big>This scaling property can not be applied for discrete-time impulse.</big></p>
        <p><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </big><blink><a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=618&amp;cnt=1#link9"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big>Top<img alt="" src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" style="width: 19px; height: 19px;" align="absMiddle"></big></span></a></blink></p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><big>         </big></p>
        <p><a name="link14"><strong><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big>Real and Complex Exponential Signal</big></span><big><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);">:</span></big></strong>&nbsp;</a></p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><big>Exponential signal is of two types. These two type of signals are real exponential signal and complex exponential signal</big> <big>which are given below.</big></p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><big>         </big></p>
